Social Differentials in Health Within and Between Populations
INTRODUCTION
Between 1965 and 1990, life expectancy for both men and
women improved by six years (from sixty-eight to seventy four and from seventy-four to eighty, respectively) in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) countries. There were even greater improvements in much of the rest of the world: eight years for men and nine years for women (from forty-one to forty-nine and from forty-three to fifty-two, respectively) in sub-Saharan Africa; and fourteen years for both men and women (from forty-six to sixty and from forty-four to fifty-eight, respectively) in India. It is a fair guess that improvements in life expectancy are attended by improvements in health status. Why are things getting better? This question is of much interest to demographers but, judging by papers in the major medical journals, of little interest to doctors, with a few notable exceptions.1 We all have ready answers to why life expectancy has improved in the poor countries of the world: improved sanitation, immuniza tion, health education, medical care, food, education, and economic development. (These answers, though obvious, may not all be cor rect.) The situation is more complex. It is not so easy to produce an answer to why life expectancy has improved in the richer countries of the world. If we believe that there is a link between wealth and health, one possible answer is that the rich countries have become richer. There are two problems with this rather simple approach. First, we do not
