Why did life expectancy in Japan increase so dramatically? Certainly not because of improved behaviors: their dietary fat intake in creased during this period, and smoking is prevalent. Furthermore, they spend little on medical care. Could it be that Japan's health success was tied up with its economic success? This might also explain Singapore's improved life expectancy and the lack of im provement in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe. Such differences may relate more to socioeconomic differentials than simply to average prosperity.
The second major irregularity in the pattern of overall improve ment is the difference in mortality rates among socioeconomic groups within countries. Figure 2 compares mortality rates in the United States in 1960 and 1986 according to level of education.4 Although mortality rates declined in all cases, the decline was greater for those who received more education. A similar scenario was reported in England and Wales.5 In addition, comparisons of mortality rates of those in lower status (manual) and those in higher status (nonmanual) occupations show a widening gap between the two groups. Figure 2. Death Rates in 1960 and 1986 among Whites Twenty-five through Sixty-four Years of Age, according to Sex and Educational
