This picture of a widening gap in mortality rates between socio economic groups at a time of overall improvement has attracted criticism.6 It has been argued that, in the United Kingdom, the apparent higher relative mortality of those in lower social classes applies to a dwindling portion of the population. The US analyses allowed for this by comparing relative mortality for constant per centiles of the distribution in the two time periods. The disparity in health status between socioeconomic groups is not disappearing as overall health status of the population improves.
HEALTH, HEALTH CARE, WHO CARES?
When health is the subject of news reports, which is quite often these days, it generally takes one of two forms: titillating snippets that supply a dedicated readership with a wide range of advice, often conflicting, on the life-style route to eternal life; and the funding and organization of health care. The first of these, the life style advice, may have some impact on the health of a small minor
ity of interested people, but neither is likely to have much impact on the health status of the population as a whole. Thomas McKeown, one of the few to be interested in discovering the determinants of the decades-long improvement in health, argued persuasively that improvements came from nutrition and environmental change, not from advances in medical care.7
There is evidence that suggests that extending medical coverage to the whole population is unlikely materially to influence socioeco nomic differences in life expectancy.8 Why, then, does health-care reform top the political and public agenda in the United States? That nation spends about one-seventh of its national income on medical care. Keeping costs under control will help individuals and companies who have to foot the bill. And extending coverage to those who are presently uninsured will bring the United States more in line with other advanced countries.
If we take life expectancy to be a measure of a country's health status, the United States, despite leading the world in medical-care expenditure, trails rather badly. In 1991, life expectancy for men in the United States was seventy-two years, which was among the worst in the OECD countries.9 This pales in comparison to Japan (seventy-six years), Sweden and Hong Kong (seventy-five years),
