and Norway and Switzerland (seventy-four years). For women, the United States ranked fourteenth out of twenty-two.
The medical profession, unsurprisingly, is concerned principally with the diagnosis and treatment of disease. There is a commitment to investigating the mechanisms of disease, with a view to improv ing treatment. To the extent that prevention has been discovered, by and large it follows the traditional medical approach of altering the risk status of individuals. As Geoffrey Rose has shown, unless an effort is made to change the risk status of whole populations, the impact on public health will be limited.10
Recently, the governments of many countries have set population health targets. In the United Kingdom, The Health of the Nation chose five key areas and set targets for the year 2000 and beyond.11 In laying out a strategy for how these targets might be achieved, the National Health Service was seen as central but there was explicit recognition that there are determinants of health that lie outside the health-care system. The contradiction is that unfortunately health ranks high on the agenda only of the Department of Health; other areas of public policy that potentially have a profound influence on health do not usually have health as a policy goal. There is, for example, little explicit recognition that economic and social policies may have a profound influence on the health of the population.
One reason for studying the correlation between socioeconomic differences and health is the insight it provides into social and economic influences on health. Social variations in health status were acknowledged in The Health of the Nation, but the conclu sion was that the knowledge base was insufficient to recommend specific actions. Taking actions that reduce these differences is not only important as a social goal, but without reductions in socioeco nomic differences in health the ability to meet health targets for the whole of society will be reduced.
SOCIOECONOMIC DIFFERENCES WITHIN COUNTRIES: THE WHITEHALL STUDIES
Many studies have shown a relation between various measures of social position and morbidity and mortality.12 In the original Whitehall study of British civil servants,13 we classified men by grade of
