The relation between social position and sickness absence rates holds for short spells of absence (seven days or fewer) as well as for long spells that require a certificate signed by a doctor. If all illness is a mix of biological, psychological, and social dysfunctions, it might be that short spells of absence reflect more of the psycholog ical and social aspects of illness, and long spells more of the biolog ical aspects of illness. Even if short spells reflect psychological and social functioning, not "true" illness, it is interesting that the social gradient in absence rates is identical for short and long spells. One possible reason for this is that the factors responsible for the social gradient in social and psychological functioning are similar to those responsible for the social gradient in "true" illness.
