in life expectancy correlated with changes in income distribution. Among six countries for which these data were available, Japan had the greatest increase in equality of income distribution and the greatest increase in life expectancy. Japan now has the most equita ble distribution of income and the longest life expectancy of any OECD country. By contrast, in the United Kingdom the bottom 60 percent of households had a declining share of total income and the population had a relatively small increase in life expectancy.18
There are two broad explanations for the relation between in come inequality and life expectancy: greater income inequality implies that a greater proportion of the population lives in absolute poverty; or that the determining factors are related to inequality rather than to poverty. If there were a nonlinear relationship be tween income and life expectancy?stronger at low incomes than at high?the apparent correlation of income inequality and life ex pectancy could possibly be explained by the differing proportions of those in poverty. Wilkinson points out that this is not the most
likely explanation.19 If the criterion of income inequality is the share of income received by the bottom 10 percent, the relation with life expectancy is very much weaker than if the criterion is the share received by the bottom 60 or 70 percent. Even if increased income inequalities did result in more households in poverty, the propor
tion of the absolute poor in OECD countries is still too small to account for the size of the relation between income inequality and
life expectancy. There must be an effect of income inequality on the large bulk of the population. In other words, the main influence on life expectancy among rich countries is likely to be relative rather than absolute deprivation.
One Disease or Many?
A striking feature of social class differences in health is that the findings apply to diverse pathological conditions. In the Whitehall study, for example, the higher risk of death among those lower in the job hierarchy applied to deaths from lung cancer, other cancers, coronary heart disease (CHD), cerebrovascular disease, other car diovascular diseases, chronic bronchitis, other respiratory diseases, gastrointestinal disease, genitourinary disease, accidents, and vio lence.20 These findings have suggested that there may be certain factors that increase general susceptibility to ill health.21
