An alternative to the general susceptibility hypothesis is that a variety of specific factors are operating to explain social class differ ences in mortality. Support for this view comes from the fact that some cancers, notably those of the colon, brain, prostate, hemato poietic system, and breast, and melanoma, do not show the same social class variation as the causes listed above.22
The general susceptibility hypothesis implies that certain groups will be at a higher risk of death whatever the causes. It does not, however, deny the operation of specific causes. For example, diseases caused by smoking, such as chronic bronchitis and lung cancer, show a particularly strong social class gradient. Put another way, according to the general susceptibility hypothesis, there are un known factors that will increase risk of death from a number of diseases in addition to the known factors such as smoking. This can account for the fact that an administrator who smokes twenty cigarettes a day has a lower risk of dying from lung cancer than does a lower grade civil servant who smokes the same amount,23 even after pack-years (packs per year times the number of years a person has smoked), tar content, and the gradient in mortality from CHD among nonsmokers are taken into account.24
This increased susceptibility to CHD may well be the result of social factors. People's life courses vary, to a great extent, by social location. And negative effects on health may accumulate through out a person's life. That influences on health cluster in such a way as to produce among social groups differing degrees of disadvan tage with respect to susceptibility to most diseases is undeniable.
Unfortunately, our current level of knowledge regarding this general susceptibility does not allow us to go much beyond empirical obser
vation.
