It has been convincingly argued that the major influences on health in adulthood operate early in life,29 and it is quite possible that social position is also determined early in life. Yet, the theory regarding the childhood origins of adult disease has been criticized precisely because of the ways in which influences from early life determine the lives people lead and the social environments in which they live and work.30 It may, in fact, be these conditions of adult life that are related to ill health, and the importance of childhood conditions may therefore be indirect. Whitehall data relating height to mortality help to distinguish between the direct effects on health of early and later life experiences. For example, height, which is both environmentally and genetically influenced, predicts adult mortality independent of grade of em ployment,31 and grade of employment, which is to some extent an index of current social influences, predicts mortality independent of height. Thus, two sets of influences may affect mortality risk: fac tors from early life and current influences.
Individuals may bring more than biological characteristics from early life to adult life. Education has been shown to be a powerful predictor of health status. This may be because education is a good predictor of social status. People with higher levels of education tend to have better jobs and higher social standing, and the advan tages that go along with them. The correlation between education and adult social position may also tell us something about causal pathways. People with more education may have more life manage ment skills, which in turn may predict both adult socioeconomic circumstances and health status.
Health-Related Behaviors and Biological Risk Factors
Why are there links between social position and life-style behaviors such as smoking? There must, of course, be biological pathways underlying the link between social position and disease rates. These biological changes may, in part, result from behaviors such as diet and smoking, but they may also be the result of other influences, such as stress, acting directly on the neuroendocrine system.
Material Conditions
The Black Report emphasized the role of material conditions in causing social inequalities in health.32 Black emphasized the point
