that some people have no choice but to be exposed to certain hazards given the present distribution of income and opportunity. This can be interpreted to include psychosocial influences that are inherently related to societal position.
When poor living conditions meant polluted water, crowded, unsanitary housing, and appalling working conditions, it was easy to see how socioeconomic status related to poor health. As coun tries became wealthier, mortality rates of all social groups im proved. But why does the social gradient persist? Are we to under stand that there are residual effects of bad housing, as well as air pollution and other material conditions, that, although they affect
the lower social groups less than they used to, still affect them more than the higher social strata? If there are such residual effects, it is no surprise that they do not affect all social strata equally. Can this
be the whole explanation? In the Whitehall and Whitehall II studies, morbidity and mortal
ity varied linearly with grade of employment. It is possible, but unlikely, that the second highest grade has worse health than the highest grade because of worse housing, a poorer diet, or more pollution. It also seems unlikely that comfortable "middle class" people in Britain are suffering from the effects of material depriva
tion.
In fact, what may be important is not absolute deprivation but relative deprivation. Comparing rich countries, Wilkinson showed that it was not differences in wealth that predicted differences in life expectancy, but differences in income distribution. This goes some distance toward explaining the social gradient in health, because each group, while not necessarily deprived, will, by definition, have "less" than the group above it. Thus, the social gradient in health will vary in magnitude depending on the magnitude of the relative differences in "deprivation."
Psychosocial Factors as Potential Explanations We have established that relative deprivation is an important cause
of social differentials in health, but what does it mean and how does it operate? How could a lower position in the social hierarchy cause heart disease and cancer, among other diseases, if not by diet or
smoking?
